{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open a web browser and go to `https://git-scm.com/downloads`. You'll see the official Git download page with logos for Windows, macOS, and Linux.",
      "title": "Visit the Git Download Page"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the icon that matches your operating system (Windows, macOS, or Linux/Unix). The download should start automatically. If it doesn't, click the direct download link shown on the next page.",
      "title": "Select Your Operating System"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait for the installer file to finish downloading. Locate it in your Downloads folder — it will be named something like `Git-2.xx.x-64-bit.exe` on Windows or a `.dmg` file on macOS.",
      "title": "Download the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Double-click the downloaded file to launch the installer. On Windows, click **Yes** if a security prompt asks for permission to make changes.",
      "title": "Launch the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Next** through each screen to accept the recommended default settings. If unsure about any option, leave it as-is — the defaults work well for most users.",
      "title": "Accept the Default Settings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Install** to begin. A progress bar will appear. When it finishes, click **Finish** to close the installer. On macOS, drag Git to your Applications folder if prompted.",
      "title": "Complete the Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your terminal. On Windows, search for **Git Bash** in the Start menu. On macOS, open **Terminal** from Applications > Utilities. On Linux, open your usual terminal app.",
      "title": "Open a Terminal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. You should see output like `git version 2.xx.x`. This confirms Git installed correctly and is ready to use.",
      "title": "Verify the Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you see `command not found` instead of a version number, close and reopen your terminal, then run `git --version` again. Reopening reloads your system's path so the terminal can find Git.",
      "title": "Troubleshoot If Needed"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Pull over onto a flat, solid surface away from traffic. Turn on your hazard lights and set the parking brake. You should feel the car sit firmly in place with no rolling.",
      "title": "Park Safely and Secure the Car"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place a wheel chock, brick, or heavy rock against the tire diagonally opposite the flat. This blocks the car from rolling while it's lifted.",
      "title": "Chock the Opposite Wheel"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take out your spare tire, jack, and lug wrench, usually stored under the trunk floor or mounted in the cargo area. Set them near the flat tire within easy reach.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fit the lug wrench onto the first lug nut and turn counterclockwise about a quarter turn to break it loose. Do NOT remove it yet. Loosen each nut this way while the tire is still on the ground.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slide the jack under the metal jack point behind the flat tire, usually a reinforced notch along the frame. Check your owner's manual if unsure. The jack head should rest firmly against solid metal.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the jack handle clockwise until the flat tire lifts about 6 inches off the ground. Raise it high enough that the inflated spare will fit. The car should feel stable, not wobbly.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unscrew each loosened lug nut the rest of the way by hand and place them together in a safe spot, like a hubcap or your pocket. Losing one means you can't reattach the wheel.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the tire with both hands and pull it straight toward you off the wheel bolts. If it's stuck, tap the back edge with your hand to loosen it. Set the flat aside flat on the ground.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Bring fresh, cold water to a boil, then let it rest for about 30 seconds. You want water around \\(200^\\circ F\\) (just off the boil). Prepare enough for your French press capacity.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure your coffee beans using a ratio of about 1 gram of coffee per 15 grams of water. For a standard cup, use roughly 2 tablespoons of beans. A kitchen scale gives the most consistent results.",
      "title": "Measure the Beans"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grind the beans to a coarse, even texture that looks like sea salt or breadcrumbs. If the grind feels powdery or fine, adjust your grinder coarser to avoid a bitter, muddy cup.",
      "title": "Grind Coarsely"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour a little hot water into the empty French press, swirl it around, then discard it. The glass should feel warm to the touch. This keeps your brew temperature stable.",
      "title": "Preheat the Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add the coffee grounds into the warmed, empty French press. Give it a gentle shake so the grounds sit level across the bottom.",
      "title": "Add the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour just enough hot water to soak all the grounds, about twice the weight of the coffee. You should see the grounds puff up and bubble. Wait 30 seconds to let it bloom and release gas.",
      "title": "Bloom the Coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the remaining hot water steadily until the press is nearly full. Stir gently with a spoon so all grounds are wet. You should see an even, dark surface with no dry clumps.",
      "title": "Add the Rest of the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set the lid on top with the plunger pulled all the way up. Do not press down yet. Start a timer for 4 minutes to let the coffee steep.",
      "title": "Place the Lid and Steep"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the timer hits 4 minutes, press the plunger down slowly and steadily with even pressure. It should take about 20 seconds. If it feels too hard, your grind is too fine.",
      "title": "Plunge Slowly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee into your cup right away so it doesn't over-extract. Serve immediately. You should have a rich, clean cup with no gritty grounds. Enjoy your French press coffee!",
      "title": "Pour and Serve"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Choose a spot that gets at least 6-8 hours of direct sunlight each day. Check that the area has good drainage by looking for places where water doesn't pool after rain.",
      "title": "Pick a Sunny Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull out all weeds, grass, and rocks from the bed by hand or with a hand trowel. Toss any large debris aside. The surface should look clear and bare when you're done.",
      "title": "Clear the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push a garden fork or spade about 8-12 inches deep into the soil, then lift and turn it over. Work across the entire bed until the soil feels loose and crumbly, not packed.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Squeeze a handful of soil. If it holds a tight ball and won't crumble, add coarse sand. If it falls apart instantly, it's sandy. This tells you what to amend next.",
      "title": "Test the Soil Texture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2-3 inch layer of compost or well-rotted manure evenly across the top of the bed. The surface should look dark and even, covering all the loosened soil.",
      "title": "Add Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your fork or spade to mix the compost into the top 6-8 inches of soil. Keep turning until the compost is blended in and you can no longer see a separate layer on top.",
      "title": "Mix in the Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sprinkle a balanced granular fertilizer over the bed, following the amount listed on the package label. Rake it lightly into the top 2-3 inches of soil so it's evenly distributed.",
      "title": "Work in Fertilizer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your soil pH with a test kit. Tomatoes prefer a pH of \\(6.2\\) to \\(6.8\\). If it reads too low, mix in garden lime; if too high, add elemental sulfur per the package rate.",
      "title": "Adjust the pH"
    },
    {
      "text": "Drag a rake across the top to level the bed and break up any clumps. The surface should be smooth, flat, and free of large lumps when finished.",
      "title": "Rake Smooth and Level"
    },
    {
      "text": "Water the bed slowly until the top 6 inches feel moist but not soggy. Let it rest for a day or two. Damp, crumbly, easy-to-dig soil means your bed is ready for tomatoes.",
      "title": "Water and Settle"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Lay your fabric flat on a large, clean table with the wrong side facing up. Smooth out any wrinkles with your hands. If the fabric is very creased, iron it first so your measurements stay accurate.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Fabric Surface"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using a measuring tape, mark a rectangle **27 inches wide by 21 inches tall** for the pillow front. Make small dots with a fabric marker at each corner. This is the standard size for a **standard pillow**.",
      "title": "Measure the Pillow Front"
    },
    {
      "text": "Line up your ruler between the corner dots and draw straight connecting lines with the fabric marker. You should see a complete rectangle outlined on the fabric.",
      "title": "Draw the Cutting Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure and mark a second rectangle **27 inches wide by 27 inches tall** for the back envelope panel. Draw its outline the same way. You'll cut this piece in half later to create the envelope opening.",
      "title": "Mark the Back Panel"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place your paper pattern piece on top of one marked rectangle, aligning its edges with your drawn lines. Insert straight pins every 3 to 4 inches through both the pattern and the fabric to hold them together.",
      "title": "Pin the Pattern in Place"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push each pin in and back out so it lies flat against the fabric. Pins should stay inside the drawn lines, not crossing them, so your scissors have a clear path.",
      "title": "Secure the Pins Flat"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut along the drawn lines using sharp fabric scissors. Keep the fabric flat and cut with long, smooth strokes. You should get a clean, straight edge with no jagged spots.",
      "title": "Cut the Front Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut out the back panel along its lines the same way. Then cut this square in half so you have **two pieces measuring 27 by 13.5 inches**. These overlap to form the envelope back.",
      "title": "Cut the Back Panels"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gently pull out all straight pins and set them in your pin cushion. Lay out your three pieces: one front and two back panels. If the edges look straight and even, your fabric is cut and ready to sew.",
      "title": "Remove Pins and Check Pieces"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Choose a clip-on tuner, a tuner app, or an online tuner. Turn it on and make sure it's set to standard chromatic mode. You should see a display that shows note names like E, A, D, G, B.",
      "title": "Get Your Tuner Ready"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sit in a quiet spot and rest the guitar on your leg. Attach the clip-on tuner to the headstock, or set your phone close enough to hear the strings clearly. Keep background noise low so the tuner reads accurately.",
      "title": "Position Your Guitar and Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the thickest string, closest to the ceiling when you hold the guitar. This is the low E string, string 6. Its target note is **E**. You'll tune the strings in order from thickest to thinnest.",
      "title": "Find the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the low E string once and watch the tuner. It should display an **E**. If it shows a note below E, tighten the tuning peg slowly; if above, loosen it. Turn the peg gently while plucking again.",
      "title": "Play the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Adjust the peg until the tuner needle sits in the center and the note reads exactly **E**. Most tuners turn green or show a steady center mark when the pitch is correct. Pluck once more to confirm it holds.",
      "title": "Tune Low E to Center"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the next string, string 5, and tune it to **A**. Turn the peg until the tuner reads A and centers. If it reads G or below, tighten; if it reads B or above, loosen.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck string 4 and tune it to **D**. Adjust the peg slowly while plucking until the tuner shows a centered D. Give the string a moment to settle, then pluck again to check.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck string 3 and tune it to **G**. Watch the tuner and adjust until it reads a steady, centered G. Turn the peg in small amounts so you don't overshoot the note.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck string 2 and tune it to **B**. Adjust the peg until the tuner centers on B and turns green or steady. This string is thinner, so make gentle adjustments to avoid over-tightening.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string, string 1, and tune it to **E**. This is the high E. Adjust carefully, as thin strings respond quickly and can snap if over-tightened. Confirm the tuner reads a centered E.",
      "title": "Tune the High E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Play each string one more time from low E to high E: **E, A, D, G, B, E**. New strings stretch and drift, so re-tune any string that has slipped. When all six read centered, your guitar is in standard tuning.",
      "title": "Check All Strings Again"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn your camera's mode dial to **M** (Manual). This gives you full control over ISO, aperture, and shutter speed. You should see the M indicator light up on your top screen or viewfinder.",
      "title": "Switch to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter button halfway to activate the light meter. Look for the exposure scale at the bottom of your viewfinder, marked from `-3` to `+3` with a moving indicator showing your current exposure level.",
      "title": "Find the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set ISO to your base value, usually `100` or `200`, using the ISO button. In bright daylight this keeps images clean. Raise it only later if the scene is too dark. You should see the ISO number update on your display.",
      "title": "Set a Low Base ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the main dial to choose your aperture, shown as an f-number like `f/8`. Use a lower number (`f/2.8`) for a blurry background or a higher number (`f/11`) for sharpness front to back. Watch the f-value change on screen.",
      "title": "Set Your Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the shutter speed dial while watching the exposure meter. Adjust until the indicator sits at `0` (center). A faster speed like `1/500` darkens the image; a slower speed like `1/60` brightens it.",
      "title": "Adjust Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confirm the meter indicator rests at the center `0` mark. If it points toward `+`, your shot is too bright; toward `-`, too dark. Nudge shutter speed or aperture until it centers.",
      "title": "Check the Meter Balance"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image is still too dark at your slowest safe shutter speed, raise ISO one step, for example from `100` to `200` or `400`. Recheck the meter and rebalance to center. Expect slightly more grain at higher ISO.",
      "title": "Raise ISO if Still Dark"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter fully to take the photo. Review it on the LCD and open the histogram. A well-exposed image shows the graph spread across the middle without tall spikes crushed against the far left or right edges.",
      "title": "Take the Shot and Review"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the histogram is too far left, brighten by slowing the shutter, opening the aperture, or raising ISO. Too far right? Do the opposite. Adjust one setting at a time and reshoot until the exposure looks right.",
      "title": "Fine-Tune and Reshoot"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand tall with your feet shoulder-width apart. Point your toes slightly outward, about 5 to 15 degrees. You should feel your weight balanced evenly across both feet.",
      "title": "Set Your Stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press your feet firmly into the floor and imagine spreading them apart to grip the ground. Your arches should feel supported, not collapsed inward. This creates a stable base for the squat.",
      "title": "Root Your Feet"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lift your chest and pull your shoulders down and back. Keep your gaze forward at a fixed point. Your spine should feel long and straight, not rounded or arched.",
      "title": "Brace Your Core and Chest"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a deep breath into your belly and tighten your abdominal muscles as if bracing for a light punch. You should feel your midsection firm up all the way around, not just in front.",
      "title": "Engage Your Core"
    },
    {
      "text": "Reach both arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height, or clasp your hands at your chest. This counterbalances your body as you descend and helps you stay upright.",
      "title": "Position Your Arms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Begin the movement by pushing your hips back, as if reaching for a chair behind you. Then bend your knees to lower down. Your hips should move back and down together, not just straight down.",
      "title": "Initiate the Descent"
    },
    {
      "text": "As you lower, guide your knees outward so they track in line with your toes. You should NOT see your knees caving inward. Keep your heels flat on the floor throughout.",
      "title": "Track Your Knees"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue lowering until your hip crease is level with or just below your knees. If your heels lift or your back rounds, stop at your comfortable depth. Your chest should stay lifted.",
      "title": "Reach Squat Depth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pause briefly at the bottom. Check that your weight is on your midfoot and heels, your chest is up, and your knees point over your toes. This is the proper bottom position.",
      "title": "Check the Bottom Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press through your heels and midfoot to stand back up. Drive your hips forward as you rise and keep your knees pushed out. You should return to a tall standing position with locked-out hips.",
      "title": "Drive Back Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "Repeat the movement 5 times slowly, focusing on each cue. You know your form is correct when your heels stay grounded, knees track over toes, and your back stays flat throughout.",
      "title": "Practice the Full Rep"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe uma tigela grande, os ingredientes secos, água morna, fermento biológico seco, açúcar, sal, farinha de trigo e óleo. A água deve estar em torno de 37°C, morna ao toque, nunca quente.",
      "title": "Reúna os ingredientes e utensílios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela pequena, misture \\(200\\,\\text{ml}\\) de água morna com 1 colher de chá de açúcar e 10g de fermento biológico seco. Mexa levemente e deixe descansar por 10 minutos.",
      "title": "Ative o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Após 10 minutos, observe a mistura. Ela deve formar uma espuma cremosa na superfície. Se isso acontecer, o fermento está ativo. Se não espumar, descarte e recomece com fermento novo.",
      "title": "Confirme a ativação do fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Na tigela grande, coloque 500g de farinha de trigo e 1 colher de chá de sal. Misture com uma colher para distribuir o sal por toda a farinha. Faça um buraco no centro, formando um espaço para os líquidos.",
      "title": "Misture os ingredientes secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje o fermento ativado no buraco central da farinha. Adicione 2 colheres de sopa de óleo. Misture com uma colher, puxando a farinha das bordas para o centro, até formar uma massa grudenta.",
      "title": "Adicione os líquidos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Transfira a massa para uma superfície levemente enfarinhada. Sove empurrando a massa com a base das mãos, dobrando-a de volta e girando. Continue por cerca de 10 minutos.",
      "title": "Comece a sova"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pressione a massa com o dedo. Ela deve voltar lentamente à forma. A massa estará lisa, elástica e não grudará mais nas mãos. Se ainda estiver pegajosa, sove por mais alguns minutos.",
      "title": "Teste o ponto da massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa em uma bola e coloque em uma tigela untada com óleo. Cubra com um pano úmido. A massa está pronta para a próxima etapa: o descanso e a fermentação.",
      "title": "Finalize a preparação"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Localiza la llave de paso bajo el lavabo y gírala en sentido horario hasta que quede firme. Si no encuentras una allí, cierra la llave principal de la casa. Abre el grifo para confirmar que ya no sale agua.",
      "title": "Cierra el paso de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cierra el tapón del desagüe o coloca un trapo sobre él. Así evitarás que tornillos o piezas pequeñas caigan por el drenaje mientras trabajas.",
      "title": "Tapa el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Con un desarmador plano, retira la tapa decorativa de la manija (suele tener una marca roja/azul o el logo). Debajo verás el tornillo que sujeta la manija.",
      "title": "Quita la tapa decorativa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa un desarmador de estrella o plano para aflojar el tornillo central. Guárdalo en un recipiente. Luego jala la manija hacia arriba para retirarla del vástago.",
      "title": "Retira la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Con una llave ajustable, gira la tuerca de sujeción en sentido antihorario. Sostén la base del grifo con la otra mano para que no se mueva.",
      "title": "Afloja la tuerca de retención"
    },
    {
      "text": "Extrae con cuidado el cartucho o vástago tirando hacia arriba. Observa su posición para volver a colocarlo igual. Este es el mecanismo interno que controla el flujo.",
      "title": "Saca el cartucho o vástago"
    },
    {
      "text": "En la base del vástago verás una arandela de goma (empaque) sujeta por un tornillo. Retira ese tornillo y quita la arandela vieja, que suele estar aplastada o agrietada.",
      "title": "Inspecciona el empaque dañado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca una arandela nueva del mismo tamaño y grosor y ajústala con su tornillo. Si el asiento del cartucho tiene juntas tóricas (O-rings) resecas, reemplázalas también.",
      "title": "Coloca el empaque nuevo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aplica un poco de grasa de silicona en las juntas nuevas. Esto facilita el sellado y evita que la goma se reseque rápido.",
      "title": "Lubrica las juntas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inserta el cartucho o vástago en la misma posición en que lo sacaste. Debe entrar sin forzar. Vuelve a colocar la tuerca de retención y apriétala firme con la llave.",
      "title": "Reinstala el cartucho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la manija sobre el vástago, ajusta el tornillo central y presiona la tapa decorativa hasta escuchar un clic. Verifica que la manija gire con suavidad.",
      "title": "Vuelve a armar la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gira la llave de paso en sentido antihorario para restablecer el agua lentamente. Abrir despacio evita golpes de presión en las tuberías.",
      "title": "Abre el paso de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre y cierra el grifo varias veces. Observa la base y la manija: no debe haber goteo ni fugas. Si aún gotea, revisa que la tuerca esté bien apretada y el empaque bien colocado.",
      "title": "Comprueba que no haya fugas"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Make sure your document is open on screen and you have content you want to keep. Look for the document title at the top of the window to confirm you're working in the right file.",
      "title": "Confirm Your Document Is Open"
    },
    {
      "text": "Move your cursor to the top-left corner and click the **File** menu. A dropdown menu will appear with options like New, Open, Save, and Print.",
      "title": "Open the File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Save** in the dropdown menu. If this is a new document, a dialog box will appear asking where to save it. If it's already been saved before, the file updates instantly.",
      "title": "Click Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the dialog box, click a folder in the left panel, such as Documents or Desktop, to choose where your file will be stored. The chosen location will appear in the path bar at the top.",
      "title": "Choose a Save Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **File name** field and type a clear, descriptive name for your document, such as `Budget Report`. Avoid special characters like `\\ / : * ?` which aren't allowed in filenames.",
      "title": "Name Your File"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **Save** button in the bottom-right corner of the dialog box. The box will close and you'll return to your document, now saved under the name you chose.",
      "title": "Click the Save Button"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check the title bar at the top of the window. It should now show your file name instead of a generic label like *Untitled*. This confirms your work is saved.",
      "title": "Verify the Save Worked"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press `Ctrl + S` on Windows or `Cmd + S` on Mac to save quickly as you continue working. Use this often so you never lose your latest changes.",
      "title": "Save Again With a Shortcut"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place your motherboard on top of its anti-static bag on a flat, non-conductive surface. Wear an anti-static wrist strap or touch a grounded metal object first. You'll build most components onto the board before mounting it in the case.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Workspace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lift the CPU socket retention arm on the motherboard. Align the golden triangle on the CPU corner with the matching triangle on the socket. Lower the CPU straight down without force, then close the arm. It should seat flush with no gaps.",
      "title": "Install the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the clips on both ends of a RAM slot. Match the notch on the RAM stick to the ridge in the slot. Press firmly on both ends until you hear a click and the clips snap upward on their own. Repeat for each stick.",
      "title": "Install the RAM"
    },
